  <!-- Limitations and Warnings -->
  <section class="py-16 md:py-20">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="text-center mb-12">
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-100 mb-4 tracking-tight">Limitations and Warnings</h2>
        <div class="gold-divider mb-4" />
      </div>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div class="calculator-card p-6 border-l-4 border-l-red-400">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
            <svg class="h-6 w-6 text-red-500 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 9v2m0 4h.01m-6.938 4h13.856c1.54 0 2.502-1.667 1.732-2.5L13.732 4c-.77-.833-1.964-.833-2.732 0L4.082 16.5c-.77.833.192 2.5 1.732 2.5z" /></svg>
            <h3 class="font-serif font-semibold text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-100">Distance Reduces Accuracy</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">The further you extrapolate beyond your data range, the less reliable the prediction. A prediction at 2x the data range is far less trustworthy than one at 1.1x.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="calculator-card p-6 border-l-4 border-l-amber-400">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
            <svg class="h-6 w-6 text-amber-500 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9.663 17h4.673M12 3v1m6.364 1.636l-.707.707M21 12h-1M4 12H3m3.343-5.657l-.707-.707m2.828 9.9a5 5 0 117.072 0l-.548.547A3.374 3.374 0 0014 18.469V19a2 2 0 11-4 0v-.531c0-.895-.356-1.754-.988-2.386l-.548-.547z" /></svg>
            <h3 class="font-serif font-semibold text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-100">Model Assumptions</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">Each method assumes a specific mathematical relationship. If the real-world process changes behavior (e.g., market crash), the model won't capture it. Always combine math with domain knowledge.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="calculator-card p-6 border-l-4 border-l-orange-400">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
            <svg class="h-6 w-6 text-orange-500 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 10V3L4 14h7v7l9-11h-7z" /></svg>
            <h3 class="font-serif font-semibold text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-100">Outlier Sensitivity</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">A single outlier can dramatically skew the fitted curve and resulting predictions. Always inspect your data for anomalies before extrapolating. Consider removing or adjusting outliers.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="calculator-card p-6 border-l-4 border-l-purple-400">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
            <svg class="h-6 w-6 text-purple-500 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M7 21a4 4 0 01-4-4V5a2 2 0 012-2h4a2 2 0 012 2v12a4 4 0 01-4 4zm0 0h12a2 2 0 002-2v-4a2 2 0 00-2-2h-2.343M11 7.343l1.657-1.657a2 2 0 012.828 0l2.829 2.829a2 2 0 010 2.828l-8.486 8.485M7 17h.01" /></svg>
            <h3 class="font-serif font-semibold text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-100">Overfitting with Polynomials</h3>
          </div>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">High-degree polynomials can fit training data perfectly but oscillate wildly outside the range (Runge's phenomenon). Stick to degree 2-3 unless you have strong justification.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="py-16 md:py-20 bg-gradient-to-b from-neutral-50/50 to-white dark:from-neutral-900/50 dark:to-neutral-950">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
      <FAQ locale={locale} items={[
        { question: 'What is extrapolation?', answer: 'Extrapolation is the process of estimating unknown values by extending a known sequence of values or facts beyond the area that is certainly known. It uses mathematical models to predict future or past values based on existing trends in your data.', category: 'general', display: true },
        { question: 'What is linear extrapolation?', answer: 'Linear extrapolation uses a straight line (y = mx + b) to extend the trend of existing data points. It assumes a constant rate of change and works best when the data follows a roughly linear pattern. This is the simplest and most commonly used extrapolation method.', category: 'calculator', display: true },
        { question: 'What is exponential extrapolation?', answer: 'Exponential extrapolation models data that grows or decays at a rate proportional to its current value, following y = a·e^(bx). It is commonly used for population growth, compound interest, viral spread, and radioactive decay calculations. All Y values must be positive.', category: 'calculator', display: true },
        { question: 'How accurate is extrapolation?', answer: 'The accuracy of extrapolation depends on how well the chosen model fits the data and how far beyond the observed range you predict. The R² score and confidence level provided by our calculator help you assess reliability. Predictions close to the data range with high R² values are generally more reliable.', category: 'technical', display: true },
        { question: 'What is R² score?', answer: 'R² (coefficient of determination) measures how well the regression model fits the observed data. Values range from 0 to 1, where 1 indicates a perfect fit and 0 means the model explains none of the variance. An R² above 0.9 indicates an excellent fit, while below 0.5 suggests a poor model choice.', category: 'technical', display: true },
        { question: 'What is the difference between extrapolation and interpolation?', answer: 'Interpolation estimates values between known data points (within the observed range), while extrapolation estimates values beyond the known data range. Interpolation is generally more accurate because it is bounded by existing observations, whereas extrapolation carries more uncertainty the further you go from known data.', category: 'general', display: true },
        { question: 'How many data points do I need for extrapolation?', answer: 'At minimum, you need 2 data points for linear, exponential, and logarithmic methods. Quadratic extrapolation requires at least 3 points, and polynomial (cubic) requires at least 4 points. However, more data points generally produce more reliable models, especially for methods that fit more parameters.', category: 'calculator', display: true },
        { question: 'Which extrapolation method should I use?', answer: 'Choose based on your data pattern: Linear for steady, constant-rate trends; Exponential for accelerating growth or decay; Logarithmic for diminishing returns (fast initial change that slows); Polynomial for complex curves with peaks and valleys; Quadratic for simple parabolic (U-shaped) relationships. Check the R² score to confirm your choice.', category: 'general', display: true },
        { question: 'Is my data stored on your servers?', answer: 'No. All calculations are performed entirely in your browser using JavaScript. Your data never leaves your device, and we do not store any personal information or calculation inputs on our servers. This calculator is 100% client-side and private.', category: 'general', display: true },
        { question: 'Can I download my results?', answer: 'Yes! After calculating, you can export your results as CSV (data table), PNG (chart image), or PDF (full report with equation and chart). Click the export buttons that appear below the results section.', category: 'calculator', display: true },
        { question: 'What does the confidence indicator mean?', answer: 'The confidence indicator is derived from the R² score and reflects how well the mathematical model fits your data. A confidence of 95%+ means the model explains over 95% of the variance in your data. Lower confidence values suggest the model may not be the best choice for your data pattern.', category: 'technical', display: true },
        { question: 'Why does polynomial extrapolation give wild results?', answer: 'High-degree polynomials can exhibit Runge\'s phenomenon — oscillating wildly at the edges of and beyond the data range. This is why we limit the polynomial degree to 3 (cubic). For safer extrapolation with complex data, try quadratic or use multiple methods and compare results.', category: 'technical', display: true },
      ]} />
    </div>
  </section>

